'''Elizabeth S. Anderson''' (born 5 December 1959) is an American philosopher. She is Arthur F. Thurnau Professor and John Dewey Distinguished University Professor of Philosophy and Women's Studies at the [[University of Michigan]] and is a notable American philosopher specializing in moral and political philosophy. Anderson is currently the chair of the University of Michigan's Department of Philosophy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lsa.umich.edu/philosophy/people/faculty/elizabeth-anderson.html|title=Elizabeth Anderson {{!}} U-M LSA Philosophy|website=lsa.umich.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref><!-- I understand it's clarified later, but her positions as the Arthur F. Thurnau Professor and John Dewey could be better described for clarity. -->

==Education and career==
Anderson received a B.A. with high honors in philosophy with a minor in economics from [[Swarthmore College]] in 1981.  In 1987 Anderson completed a Ph.D. in Philosophy at [[Harvard University]].  She was a visiting instructor of philosophy at Swarthmore College 1985-86 and took up a position at the [[University of Michigan]] in 1987.  She was Associate Professor of Philosophy and Women's Studies 1993-1999 and was promoted to professor in 1999.  In 1994, she was named Arthur F. Thurnau Professor to recognize her dedication to undergraduate education with a demonstrable impact on the intellectual development and lives of her students.  In 2005 she  was named John Rawls Collegiate Professor of Philosophy and Women's Studies, and in 2013 the John Dewey Distinguished University Professor of Philosophy and Women's Studies.  Anderson was elected to the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 2008.<ref name=Academy>{{cite web|title=Professor Elizabeth S. Anderson|url=https://www.amacad.org/content/system/search.aspx?s=Elizabeth+Anderson|publisher=American Academy of Arts & Sciences|accessdate=3 April 2014|quote=Fellow elected 2008}}</ref>  In 2013, Anderson received a [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] to support her work.<ref name=Guggen>{{cite web|title=Elizabeth S. Anderson |url=http://www.gf.org/fellows/17351-elizabeth-s-anderson |publisher=John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation |accessdate=3 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140401232132/http://www.gf.org/fellows/17351-elizabeth-s-anderson |archivedate=1 April 2014 |df= }}</ref>  Anderson was named a Progress Medal Laureate in February 2018 by the Society for Progress for her book Private Government: How Employers Rule Our Lives (and Why We Don't Talk about It).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://societyforprogress.org/themedals.html|title=The Medals {{!}} Society for Progress|last=societyforprogress.org|website=societyforprogress.org|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>

==Research and publications==
Anderson's research covers topics in [[social philosophy]], [[political philosophy]] and [[ethics]], including: democratic theory, equality in political philosophy and American law, racial integration, the ethical limits of markets, theories of value and rational choice (alternatives to [[consequentialism]] and economic theories of [[rational choice]]), the philosophies of [[John Stuart Mill]] and [[John Dewey]], and [[feminist epistemology]] and [[philosophy of science]].<ref name=Michigan>{{cite web|title=Elizabeth Anderson|url=http://www.lsa.umich.edu/philosophy/people/faculty/ci.andersonelizabeth_ci.detail |publisher=Department of Philosophy, University of Michigan|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref>

Anderson's book ''The Imperative of Integration'',<ref name=Imperative>{{cite book | last = Anderson | first = Elizabeth | title = Imperative of integration | publisher = Princeton Univ Press | location = S.l | year = 2013 | isbn = 9780691158112 }}</ref> was winner of the [[American Philosophical Association]]'s 2011 Joseph B. Gittler Award, for "an outstanding scholarly contribution in the field of the philosophy of one or more of the social sciences."<ref name=Gittler>{{cite web|title=Joseph B. Gittler Award - Previous Winners|url=http://www.apaonline.org/?page=gittler&terms=%22elizabeth+and+s+and+anderson+and+2011+and+joseph+and+b+and+gittler+and+award%22|publisher=The American Philosophical Association|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> She is also author of ''Value in Ethics and Economics'',<ref name=Value>{{cite book | last = Anderson | first = Elizabeth | title = Value in ethics and economics | publisher = Harvard University Press | location = Cambridge, Massachusetts | year = 1993 | isbn = 9780674931909 }}</ref> and dozens of articles.<ref name=Works>{{cite web|title=Works by Elizabeth Anderson|url=http://philpapers.org/s/Elizabeth%20Anderson|publisher=The PhilPapers Foundation|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref>

