'''Phintys''' was a [[Pythagoreanism|Pythagorean]] philosopher, probably from the third century BC.  She wrote a work on the correct behaviour of women, two extracts of which are preserved by [[Stobaeus]].

According to Stobaeus, Phintys was the daughter of Callicrates,<ref>Stobaeus, iv 23.11</ref> who is otherwise unknown.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=84}}  Holger Thesleff suggests that this Callicrates might be identified with [[Callicratidas]], a Spartan general who died at the [[Battle of Arginusae]].{{sfn|Waithe|1987|p=26}}  If so, this would make Phintys a Spartan, and date her birth to the late fifth century BC, and her [[floruit]] to the fourth century. I. M. Plant considers this emendation "fanciful".{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=84}}  [[Iamblichus]] mentions '''Philtys''' in his list of female Pythagoreans;<ref>Iamblichus, ''Life of Pythagoras'', 267</ref> he says that she was from [[Crotone|Croton]] and that her father was called Theophrius.  I. M. Plant believes that Iamblichus' Philtys, though also a Pythagorean and similarly named, is distinct from Stobaeus' Phintys.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=84}}

Two fragments attributed to Phintys are preserved in Stobaeus.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=84}}  However, not all scholars agree that the fragments are authentic: Lefkowitz and Fant argue that the works attributed to female Pythagoreans, including Phintys, were actually rhetorical exercises written by men.{{sfn|Lefkowitz|Fant}}  They are written in the Doric dialect, and amount to about 80 lines of prose.{{sfn|Thesleff|1961|p=18}}  The language used dates to around the fourth century BC, although some features of it appear to be deliberate archaisms; it was likely actually composed in the third century BC,{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=84}} though a date as late as the second century AD was suggested by Friedrich Wilhelm in 1915.{{sfn|Thesleff|1961|p=34}}  

The fragments discuss the differences between men and women,{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=84}} and argues for chastity as the most important virtue for women.{{sfn|Wider|1986|p=36}}  She gives a series of ways that women ought to practice self-control, concluding that the most effective way is to only have sex with her husband in order to produce legitimate children.{{sfn|Wider|1986|pp=36–7}}  Along with her defence of women's chastity, Phintys argues that the practice of philosophy is appropriate for women as well as men.{{sfn|Plant|2004|p=84}}

